{"id":"2302.13414","submitter":"Krist\\'of B\\'erczi","authors":"Krist\\'of B\\'erczi, Lydia Mirabel Mendoza-Cadena, Kitti Varga","title":"Newton-type algorithms for inverse optimization II: weighted span\n  objective","comments":"47 pages, 2 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC cs.DM","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In inverse optimization problems, the goal is to modify the costs in an\nunderlying optimization problem in such a way that a given solution becomes\noptimal, while the difference between the new and the original cost functions,\ncalled the deviation vector, is minimized with respect to some objective\nfunction. The $\\ell_1$- and $\\ell_\\infty$-norms are standard objectives used to\nmeasure the size of the deviation. Minimizing the $\\ell_1$-norm is a natural\nway of keeping the total change of the cost function low, while the\n$\\ell_\\infty$-norm achieves the same goal coordinate-wise. Nevertheless, none\nof these objectives is suitable to provide a balanced or fair change of the\ncosts.\n  In this paper, we initiate the study of a new objective that measures the\ndifference between the largest and the smallest weighted coordinates of the\ndeviation vector, called the weighted span. We give a min-max characterization\nfor the minimum weighted span of a feasible deviation vector, and provide a\nNewton-type algorithm for finding one that runs in strongly polynomial time in\nthe case of unit weights.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 26 Feb 2023 21:51:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 28 Feb 2023 07:24:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-01"}
